The error in your screenshot is:

mysqli_connect(): (HY000/2002): No route to host
Connection failed: No route to host
What this means (very simple):

Your app container cannot reach the MySQL container over the network.

✅ Root Cause

You used:

--link mysqldb:mysqlcon

But inside your PHP config (config.php), the hostname is likely not mysqlcon, or networking is not resolving properly.

✅ One-Step Fix (simplest and correct way)

Instead of using --link (deprecated), run both containers in the same Docker network.

🔥 Just do this:
docker network create mynet

Then run containers like this:

docker run -d --name mysqldb --network mynet -p 3306:3306 pranay419/bloodyapp:dbimage

docker run -d --name appcont --network mynet -p 1111:80 pranay419/bloodyapp:appimage
✅ Important (VERY IMPORTANT)

In your config.php, set DB host as:

$host = "mysqldb";

👉 Because Docker automatically resolves container names as hostnames inside the same network.

🎯 Final Result
App connects to DB correctly
No “No route to host” error
Your app will open on:
http://<IP>:1111

Do it inside your Jenkins pipeline ✅ (not manually on EC2).

✅ Single Step Fix (what you should change)

Just update your Deploy stage like this:

stage ("Deploy") {
    steps {
        sh 'docker network create mynet || true'
        sh 'docker run -d --name mysqldb --network mynet -p 3306:3306 pranay419/bloodyapp:dbimage'
        sh 'docker run -d --name appcont --network mynet -p 1111:80 pranay419/bloodyapp:appimage'
    }
}
🎯 Why this works
Jenkins runs on your EC2 → so it executes Docker commands there
Network gets created automatically during pipeline run
Containers can talk using mysqldb hostname
⚠️ Small but important

Make sure in your PHP config.php:

$host = "mysqldb";
🚀 Result
No manual work needed
Fully automated deployment
Error will be fixed

❌ Error meaning
Conflict. The container name "/mysqldb" is already in use

👉 This means your previous pipeline run already created a container named mysqldb, and Docker doesn’t allow duplicate names.

✅ One-Step Fix (clean + run)

Just remove old containers before running new ones in your Deploy stage:

stage ("Deploy") {
    steps {
        sh 'docker rm -f mysqldb appcont || true'
        sh 'docker network create mynet || true'
        sh 'docker run -d --name mysqldb --network mynet -p 3306:3306 pranay419/bloodyapp:dbimage'
        sh 'docker run -d --name appcont --network mynet -p 1111:80 pranay419/bloodyapp:appimage'
    }
}
🎯 Why this works
docker rm -f → deletes old containers if they exist
|| true → prevents pipeline failure if they don’t exist
Fresh containers start every time → no conflict
🚀 Result
Pipeline will not fail
Containers recreated cleanly
Your app will connect to DB without issues

